&gt; &gt; &gt;Here&#39;s an update on my Image Enlargement eXperiment (IEX) :)
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;We&#39;re up to generation 425.  Still no where near a &#39;solution&#39;, but
&gt; &gt; &gt;proceeding.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;I found that if I installed cygwin 
&gt;(http://www.redhat.com/software/cygwin/)
&gt; &gt; &gt;on my windows box, I&#39;m able to use it as a client for the project, too.
&gt; &gt; &gt;So,
&gt; &gt; &gt;for all those out there that wanted to help, but didn&#39;t have a linux 
&gt;box,
&gt; &gt; &gt;there you go!
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;Also, Collin, there was a bug in the client that broke the auto-update
&gt; &gt; &gt;feature.  I fixed it, but you need to manually update your machine in 
&gt;order
&gt; &gt; &gt;to pick it up.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;I&#39;ve added some nice graphs to the status page.  First graph is maximum
&gt; &gt; &gt;fitness per generation.  It fluctuates a lot, because of the slightly
&gt; &gt; &gt;random
&gt; &gt; &gt;nature of the fitness evaluation process.  But I&#39;ve also plotted the
&gt; &gt; &gt;running
&gt; &gt; &gt;average, which definitely shows an upward trend.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;The second graph replaces the old HTML-based population fitness graph.  
&gt;It
&gt; &gt; &gt;is a bar graph, one bar per network, with the scale of the graph
&gt; &gt; &gt;representing the range of fitness within the population.  A zero in 
&gt;this
&gt; &gt; &gt;graph represents the minimum fitness, not a zero fitness.  Likewise, a 
&gt;max
&gt; &gt; &gt;value does not represent a solution, only the top performer.  The graph
&gt; &gt; &gt;only
&gt; &gt; &gt;shows the relative fitness between networks, not an overall fitness 
&gt;value.
&gt; &gt; &gt;The graph shows the networks in the order in which they were created, 
&gt;so
&gt; &gt; &gt;all
&gt; &gt; &gt;the elites from the previous generation appear first, followed by the
&gt; &gt; &gt;offspring for each topology.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;The next graph is harder to understand.  It is a measure of how stable, 
&gt;or
&gt; &gt; &gt;reliable, the fitness value described above is for each network.  If 
&gt;the
&gt; &gt; &gt;fitness of a network is still wildly fluctuating, then it is not very
&gt; &gt; &gt;stable.  If the fitness hasn&#39;t changed appreciably in some time (where 
&gt;time
&gt; &gt; &gt;is number of samples processed), then it will have a high stability.  
&gt;The
&gt; &gt; &gt;idea is, if we reach a point where all the networks have a stable 
&gt;fitness,
&gt; &gt; &gt;we are done for that generation (we can finish up early).  
&gt;Unfortunately,
&gt; &gt; &gt;at
&gt; &gt; &gt;this point there is one topology whose fitness values still fluctuate
&gt; &gt; &gt;wildly, so it has low stability, so the mechanism that was intended to 
&gt;help
&gt; &gt; &gt;the experiment get through generations faster isn&#39;t yet able to do so.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;The final graph is a fitness histogram.  The bars at the extreme left
&gt; &gt; &gt;represent the lowest fitness within the population, the bars at the 
&gt;right
&gt; &gt; &gt;represent highest fitness, and the height of the bar represent how many
&gt; &gt; &gt;networks are in that range of fitness.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;The next graph I intend to add is a pie chart, which shows the relative
&gt; &gt; &gt;investment in each topology (offspring allocation number, not 
&gt;necessarily
&gt; &gt; &gt;the same thing as actual offspring, since there is an offspring limit).
&gt; &gt; &gt;I&#39;ll try to add that today or tomorrow.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;Any comments or suggestions for the status page?  Thanks!
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;-- John
